{
  "text": "Kveder et al. [CITATION_1] presented and validated a model for the electrical activity of dislocations based on first principles analysis of carrier capture and recombination statistics for both clean dislocations and those decorated with metal impurities. Stokkan et al. [CITATION_2] have shown that, from an electrical perspective, grain boundaries can be treated as arrays of dislocations. Kveder's model involves transitions between many different energy levels. It was shown previously [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] that a simplification to one single energy level near midgap can be done effectively if the grain size is not too small (smaller than usual mc-Si material) and if the doping concentration is not too low (about 5×10 [CITATION_5] cm -3 at the usual grain size of mc-Si material). This simplification may also have the advantage that it removes a degree of freedom of the input parameters (the energy distribution of defects) and therefore captures the dynamics of phenomena in a more straightforward way [CITATION_6] . We find that at 300 K, we can match the enhanced recombination and band bending associated with metals decorating dislocations using a single-energy-level SRH model by transforming the capture cross-sections as follows:",
